Nrg1 type I expression was significantly negatively correlated with age (r = −0.846, P < 0.001), whereby Nrg1 type I levels dramatically declined both during the early postnatal (r = −0.679, P < 0.001) and prepubertal periods (r = −0.797, P < 0.001), stabilized during post puberty (r = −0.084, P = 0.774), before continuing to steadily decline throughout adulthood into aging (r = −0.449, P = 0.007). Nrg1 type II expression in the mouse PFC displayed a significant positive correlation with age (r = 0.352, P < 0.001), stemming from a gradual incline in expression levels across each lifestage ((early postnatal r = 0.089, P = 0.674; prepubertal r = 0.145, P = 0.531; postpubertal r = 0.028, P = 0.925; adulthood through aging r = 0.251, P = 0.146).

During mouse brain development, Dbn1 expression level reached its highest point at postnatal day 7 (approximately 1.8 times  higher compared to 1 day after birth), and showed a very low level at adulthood (approximately 1.8 times  lower compared to 1 day after birth). Imaging data showed that Dbn1 protein was mainly expressed in the hippocampus, ventricular zone, and cortex. The imaging data showed that Dbn1 was increasingly expressed in the extending neurites in accordance with the cell morphological changes that occur during differentiation. Obvious colocalization signals of Dbn1 with actin were found in the neurites and dendritic spines during early development but not in adult animals (60 days old). Collectively, these results suggest that Dbn1 may play a key role in mouse brain development and may regulate neuronal stem cells differentiation by filamentous actin.

In embryonic dorsal root ganglia neurons  type III sodium channel mRNA is expressed at high levels. Type III sodium channel mRNA was not detectable in control dorsal root ganglia neurons of adult rat. These results demonstrate altered expression of sodium channel mRNA in dorsal root ganglia neurons following axotomy, and suggest that in at least some dorsal root ganglia neurons, there is a de-differentiation after axotomy that includes a reversion to an embryonic mode of sodium channel expression.

The levels of the mRNAs encoding sodium channels I, II and III in various regions of the developing rat central nervous system (from embryonal day 10 to postnatal day 90) have been examined by blot hybridization analysis with specific probes. In all regions, sodium channel III mRNA attains maximum levels around birth and decreases during the first and second postnatal weeks to reach variable low adult levels. These results suggest that sodium channel III is expressed predominantly at fetal and early postnatal stages.

The expression of sodium channel alpha-subunit mRNAs I, II, III, NaG, Na6 and hNE (PN1) was examined in developing (E17-P30) hippocampus, cerebellum, spinal cord and dorsal root ganglia using non-isotopic in situ hybridization cytochemistry. Sodium channel mRNA III was more prevalent at late embryonic and early postnatal times, and was barely detectable at P30.

At embryonic day 18.5 (E18.5), no encephalopsin expression is detected in the cerebellum despite substantial levels of encephalopsin in the adjacent dorsal pons. At postnatal day 4 (P4), Purkinje cells express encephalopsin, but no stripes or gradients are clearly evident. At P20, stripes can be seen, but these are substantially more notable in the adult cerebellum.
In the cerebral cortex, the rostrocaudal gradient is absent at E18.5, P2, and P4 but becomes evident at P20 and is most prominent in the adult.

The spinal cord displays substantial encephalopsin at early stages. The highest levels of encephalopsin occur in a subset of interneurons in the ventral cord of the spinal cord at E15.5. Expression decreases at E17 and E18. At P2, encephalopsin expression is clearly restricted to the area of interneurons in the ventral horn.
